{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.08,0.16,0.39,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42405"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents with a three month history of palpitations and insomnia. She describes episodes of rapid, forceful regular heartbeats, which may occur either during exercise or when she is resting. Her sleep has become disturbed and she cannot offer a simple explanation for this. She started an exercise program for weight reduction and has managed to lose about 8 kg body weight during the previous four months. She does not have any other symptoms and is she is in good health, with no other recent illnesses. She states she does not take any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 136/62 mmHg, pulse 120/min, temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and spO2 98% on room air. Her BMI is 31. Her outstretched hands show a slight tremor. An ECG confirms a sinus tachycardia. Investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH 0.008 mU/L (0.4\u20134.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree T3 9.3 pmol/L (3.1\u20136.8 pmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree T4 46 pmol/L (12\u2013 22 pmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroglobulin 0.7 ng/mL (normal 3.5\u201377)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroglobulin antibodies (TgAb) negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound scan of thyroid is normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid scintigraphy does not show any uptake\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Graves\u0027 disease","Toxic adenoma","Subacute thyroiditis","Factitious thyrotoxicosis","Struma ovarii"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with manifestations of thyrotoxicosis including palpitations, tremor, low TSH, high T3 and T4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient may be surreptitiously ingesting thyroid hormone, or it may be contained in her weight loss regimen. In\u003Cstrong\u003E factitious thyrotoxicosis\u003C/strong\u003E serum T3 and T4 levels are increased, but the T3/T4 ratio is lower than that in the hyperthyroid patients with Graves\u2019 disease and toxic nodular goiter. The thyroid gland is usually of normal size and echogenicity. The thyroglobulin level is low and there is no uptake on RAIU.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u2019 disease\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most frequent causes of hyperthyroidism, However, this presentation lacks other clinical features such as diffuse goitre, thyroid bruit, ophthalmopathy, and pretibial myxoedema. More importantly in Graves\u2019 disease, greater increase in fT3 levels with respect to fT4 levels, elevated thyroglobulin level (Tg) and high radioactive iodine uptake (RAIU) would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E toxic adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E have similar presentation; however it would be evident on the thyroid ultrasound with an elevated Tg and high RAIU.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly stages of \u003Cstrong\u003Esubacute thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with thyrotoxicosis, with a low RAIU. However, it is characteristically associated with neck pain, heterogeneous echogenicity on thyroid US, elevated Tg level and high acute phase reactants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStruma ovarii\u003C/strong\u003E is a specialised teratoma predominantly composed of mature thyroid tissue. Only 5-8% of patients with struma ovarii have clinical signs of hyperthyroidism, more frequent presentations include: abdominal pain or mass, abnormal vaginal bleeding and ascites. Tg levels are elevated and used as marker for follow up and radioiodine uptake could be detected in the pelvis in a whole-body radioiodine scintigraphy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The diagnosis of factitious thyrotoxicosis is based upon the absence of goitre, suppressed serum Tg level, decreased radioactive iodine (RAI) uptake, and excellent response after cholestyramine treatment."],"references":["Rocchi R, Marcocci C. Thyrotoxicosis; Overview of Causes. Encyclopedia of Endocrine Diseases. 2018 Jan 1;651\u20136.","Vorasart P, Sriphrapradang C. Factitious thyrotoxicosis: how to find it. Diagnosis. 2020 Jun 1;7(2):141\u20135."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T16:26:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T16:27:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/281"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hyperthyroidism","synonyms":[],"descrip